      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Hemolysis index prediction vs. experimental measurement — primary operating point",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values at the nominal CPB operating point (4.5 L/min, 2800 RPM) were evaluated against in-vitro measurements. Predicted NIH of 0.0031 g/100 L falls within the reported scatter of published bench data. Agreement is considered satisfactory for MRL 2 purposes. The analysis references Morrison et al. (2022) bench measurements as the basis for comparison; however, no formal comparedAgainst link is recorded because the experimental dataset was obtained under a data-use agreement that restricts direct citation in structured metadata. The validation team noted that agreement within 12% is consistent with expectations for this class of model.",
      "quantitativeMetric": "NIH prediction error: 12% relative to mean experimental value",
      "passFail": "Pass"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/comparator-vad-conditions",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Hemolysis index prediction vs. VAD bench dataset — secondary operating sweep",
      "description": "CFD predictions of NIH across five flow-speed combinations were compared against the FDA benchmark hemolysis dataset (Hariharan et al., 2011), which characterises the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry under ventricular assist device (VAD) operating conditions (5–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM). Predicted NIH values matched the benchmark within 15% across all operating points. The validation team assessed this comparison as representative of the CPB operating envelope because the pump geometry and blood-damage model are identical; differences in downstream pressure head (CPB: 60–80 mmHg vs. VAD: 100–120 mmHg) were noted in passing but not treated as a comparator-scope limitation. Relative hemolysis index RH < 1 for all five CPB operating points, meeting the acceptance criterion.",
      "quantitativeMetric": "NIH prediction error across 5 operating points: 8%–15% relative to Hariharan et al. benchmark",
